 87 | ## Configuration
 88 | 
 89 | On iOS the barcode scanner plugin requires the `NSCameraUsageDescription` information property list value, which should describe why your app needs to use the camera.
 90 | 
 91 | In the `src-tauri/Info.ios.plist` file, add the following snippet:
 92 | 
 93 | ```xml title=src-tauri/Info.ios.plist
 94 | <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
 95 | <!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
 96 | <plist version="1.0">
 97 | 	<dict>
 98 | 		<key>NSCameraUsageDescription</key>
 99 | 		<string>Read QR codes</string>
100 | 	</dict>
101 | </plist>
102 | ```
103 | 
104 | ## Usage
105 | 
106 | The barcode scanner plugin is available in JavaScript.
107 | 
108 | ```javascript
109 | import { scan, Format } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-barcode-scanner';
110 | // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
111 | // const { scan, Format } = window.__TAURI__.barcodeScanner;
112 | 
113 | // `windowed: true` actually sets the webview to transparent
114 | // instead of opening a separate view for the camera
115 | // make sure your user interface is ready to show what is underneath with a transparent element
116 | scan({ windowed: true, formats: [Format.QRCode] });
117 | ```
