 84 | ## Base Configuration
 85 | 
 86 | Under `tauri.conf.json`, you have the following structure to configure the interface:
 87 | 
 88 | ```json title="src-tauri/tauri.conf.json"
 89 | {
 90 |   "plugins": {
 91 |     "cli": {
 92 |       "description": "Tauri CLI Plugin Example",
 93 |       "args": [
 94 |         {
 95 |           "short": "v",
 96 |           "name": "verbose",
 97 |           "description": "Verbosity level"
 98 |         }
 99 |       ],
100 |       "subcommands": {
101 |         "run": {
102 |           "description": "Run the application",
103 |           "args": [
104 |             {
105 |               "name": "debug",
106 |               "description": "Run application in debug mode"
107 |             },
108 |             {
109 |               "name": "release",
110 |               "description": "Run application in release mode"
111 |             }
112 |           ]
113 |         }
114 |       }
115 |     }
116 |   }
117 | }
118 | ```
119 | 
120 | :::note
121 | 
122 | All JSON configurations here are just samples, many other fields have been omitted for the sake of clarity.
123 | 
124 | :::
125 | 
126 | ## Adding Arguments
127 | 
128 | The `args` array represents the list of arguments accepted by its command or subcommand.
129 | 
130 | {/* TODO: List available configuration */}
131 | 
132 | ### Positional Arguments
133 | 
134 | A positional argument is identified by its position in the list of arguments. With the following configuration:
135 | 
136 | ```json title="src-tauri/tauri.conf.json"
137 | {
138 |   "args": [
139 |     {
140 |       "name": "source",
141 |       "index": 1,
142 |       "takesValue": true
143 |     },
144 |     {
145 |       "name": "destination",
146 |       "index": 2,
147 |       "takesValue": true
148 |     }
149 |   ]
150 | }
151 | ```
152 | 
153 | Users can run your app as `./app tauri.txt dest.txt` and the arg matches map will define `source` as `"tauri.txt"` and `destination` as `"dest.txt"`.
154 | 
155 | ### Named Arguments
156 | 
157 | A named argument is a (key, value) pair where the key identifies the value. With the following configuration:
158 | 
159 | ```json title="tauri-src/tauri.conf.json"
160 | {
161 |   "args": [
162 |     {
163 |       "name": "type",
164 |       "short": "t",
165 |       "takesValue": true,
166 |       "multiple": true,
167 |       "possibleValues": ["foo", "bar"]
168 |     }
169 |   ]
170 | }
171 | ```
172 | 
173 | Users can run your app as `./app --type foo bar`, `./app -t foo -t bar` or `./app --type=foo,bar` and the arg matches map will define `type` as `["foo", "bar"]`.
174 | 
175 | ### Flag Arguments
176 | 
177 | A flag argument is a standalone key whose presence or absence provides information to your application. With the following configuration:
178 | 
179 | ```json title="tauri-src/tauri.conf.json"
180 | {
181 |   "args": [
182 |     {
183 |       "name": "verbose",
184 |       "short": "v"
185 |     }
186 |   ]
187 | }
188 | ```
189 | 
190 | Users can run your app as `./app -v -v -v`, `./app --verbose --verbose --verbose` or `./app -vvv` and the arg matches map will define `verbose` as `true`, with `occurrences = 3`.
191 | 
192 | ## Subcommands
193 | 
194 | Some CLI applications have additional interfaces as subcommands. For instance, the `git` CLI has `git branch`, `git commit` and `git push`. You can define additional nested interfaces with the `subcommands` array:
195 | 
196 | ```json title="tauri-src/tauri.conf.json"
197 | {
198 |   "cli": {
199 |     ...
200 |     "subcommands": {
201 |       "branch": {
202 |         "args": []
203 |       },
204 |       "push": {
205 |         "args": []
206 |       }
207 |     }
208 |   }
209 | }
210 | ```
211 | 
212 | Its configuration is the same as the root application configuration, with the `description`, `longDescription`, `args`, etc.
213 | 
214 | ## Usage
215 | 
216 | The CLI plugin is available in both JavaScript and Rust.
217 | 
218 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
219 |   <TabItem label="JavaScript">
220 | 
221 | ```javascript
222 | import { getMatches } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-cli';
223 | // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
224 | // const { getMatches } = window.__TAURI__.cli;
225 | 
226 | const matches = await getMatches();
227 | if (matches.subcommand?.name === 'run') {
228 |   // `./your-app run $ARGS` was executed
229 |   const args = matches.subcommand.matches.args;
230 |   if (args.debug?.value === true) {
231 |     // `./your-app run --debug` was executed
232 |   }
233 |   if (args.release?.value === true) {
234 |     // `./your-app run --release` was executed
235 |   }
236 | }
237 | ```
238 | 
239 |   </TabItem>
240 |   <TabItem label="Rust">
241 | 
242 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs" {1, 6-18}
243 | use tauri_plugin_cli::CliExt;
244 | 
245 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
246 | pub fn run() {
247 |    tauri::Builder::default()
248 |        .plugin(tauri_plugin_cli::init())
249 |        .setup(|app| {
250 |            match app.cli().matches() {
251 |                // `matches` here is a Struct with { args, subcommand }.
252 |                // `args` is `HashMap<String, ArgData>` where `ArgData` is a struct with { value, occurrences }.
253 |                // `subcommand` is `Option<Box<SubcommandMatches>>` where `SubcommandMatches` is a struct with { name, matches }.
254 |                Ok(matches) => {
255 |                    println!("{:?}", matches)
256 |                }
257 |                Err(_) => {}
258 |            }
259 |            Ok(())
260 |        })
261 |        .run(tauri::generate_context!())
262 |        .expect("error while running tauri application");
263 | }
264 | ```
265 | 
266 |   </TabItem>
267 | </Tabs>
268 | 
269 | ## Permissions
270 | 
271 | By default all potentially dangerous plugin commands and scopes are blocked and cannot be accessed. You must modify the permissions in your `capabilities` configuration to enable these.
272 | 
273 | See the [Capabilities Overview](/security/capabilities/) for more information and the [step by step guide](/learn/security/using-plugin-permissions/) to use plugin permissions.
274 | 
275 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" ins={6}
276 | {
277 |   "$schema": "../gen/schemas/desktop-schema.json",
278 |   "identifier": "main-capability",
279 |   "description": "Capability for the main window",
280 |   "windows": ["main"],
281 |   "permissions": ["cli:default"]
282 | }
283 | ```
284 | 
