 82 | 
 83 | ## Setting up
 84 | 
 85 | ### Android
 86 | 
 87 | For [app links](https://developer.android.com/training/app-links#android-app-links), you need a server with a
 88 | `.well-known/assetlinks.json` endpoint that must return a text response in the given format:
 89 | 
 90 | ```json title=".well-known/assetlinks.json"
 91 | [
 92 |   {
 93 |     "relation": ["delegate_permission/common.handle_all_urls"],
 94 |     "target": {
 95 |       "namespace": "android_app",
 96 |       "package_name": "$APP_BUNDLE_ID",
 97 |       "sha256_cert_fingerprints": [
 98 |         $CERT_FINGERPRINT
 99 |       ]
100 |     }
101 |   }
102 | ]
103 | ```
104 | 
105 | Where `$APP_BUNDLE_ID` is the value defined on [`tauri.conf.json > identifier`] with `-` replaced with `_` and
106 | `$CERT_FINGERPRINT` is a list of SHA256 fingerprints of your app's signing certificates,
107 | see [verify Android applinks] for more information.
108 | 
109 | ### iOS
110 | 
111 | For [universal links], you need a server with a `.well-known/apple-app-site-association` endpoint that must return a JSON response
112 | in the given format:
113 | 
114 | ```json title=".well-known/apple-app-site-association"
115 | {
116 |   "applinks": {
117 |     "details": [
118 |       {
119 |         "appIDs": ["$DEVELOPMENT_TEAM_ID.$APP_BUNDLE_ID"],
120 |         "components": [
121 |           {
122 |             "/": "/open/*",
123 |             "comment": "Matches any URL whose path starts with /open/"
124 |           }
125 |         ]
126 |       }
127 |     ]
128 |   }
129 | }
130 | ```
131 | 
132 | :::note
133 | The response `Content-Type` header must be `application/json`.
134 | 
135 | The `.well-known/apple-app-site-association` endpoint must be served over HTTPS.
136 | To test localhost you can either use a self-signed TLS certificate and install it on the iOS simulator or use services like [ngrok].
137 | :::
138 | 
139 | Where `$DEVELOPMENT_TEAM_ID` is the value defined on `tauri.conf.json > tauri > bundle > iOS > developmentTeam` or the
140 | `TAURI_APPLE_DEVELOPMENT_TEAM` environment variable and `$APP_BUNDLE_ID` is the value defined on [`tauri.conf.json > identifier`].
141 | 
142 | To verify if your domain has been properly configured to expose the app associations, you can run the following command,
143 | replacing `<host>` with your actual host:
144 | 
145 | ```sh
146 | curl -v https://app-site-association.cdn-apple.com/a/v1/<host>
147 | ```
148 | 
149 | See [applinks.details](https://developer.apple.com/documentation/bundleresources/applinks/details) for more information.
150 | 
151 | ### Desktop
152 | 
153 | On Linux and Windows deep links are delivered as a command line argument to a new app process.
154 | The deep link plugin has integration with the [single instance] plugin if you prefer having a unique app instance receiving the events.
155 | 
156 | - First you must add the `deep-link` feature to the single instance plugin:
157 | 
158 | ```toml title="src-tauri/Cargo.toml"
159 | [target."cfg(any(target_os = \"macos\", windows, target_os = \"linux\"))".dependencies]
160 | tauri-plugin-single-instance = { version = "2.0.0", features = ["deep-link"] }
161 | ```
162 | 
163 | - Then configure the single instance plugin which should always be the first plugin you register:
164 | 
165 | ```rust title="src-tauri/lib.rs"
166 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
167 | pub fn run() {
168 |     let mut builder = tauri::Builder::default();
169 | 
170 |     #[cfg(desktop)]
171 |     {
172 |         builder = builder.plugin(tauri_plugin_single_instance::init(|_app, argv, _cwd| {
173 |           println!("a new app instance was opened with {argv:?} and the deep link event was already triggered");
174 |           // when defining deep link schemes at runtime, you must also check `argv` here
175 |         }));
176 |     }
177 | 
178 |     builder = builder.plugin(tauri_plugin_deep_link::init());
179 | }
180 | ```
181 | 
182 | :::warn
183 | The user could trigger a fake deep link manually by including the URL as argument.
184 | Tauri matches the command line argument against the configured schemes to mitigate this,
185 | but you should still check if the URL matches the format you expect.
186 | 
187 | This means Tauri only handles deep links for schemes that were statically configured,
188 | and schemes registered at runtime must be manually checked using [`Env::args_os`].
189 | :::
190 | 
191 | ## Configuration
192 | 
193 | Under `tauri.conf.json > plugins > deep-link`, configure the domains (mobile) and schemes (desktop) you want to associate with your application:
194 | 
195 | ```json title="tauri.conf.json"
196 | {
197 |   "plugins": {
198 |     "deep-link": {
199 |       "mobile": [
200 |         { "host": "your.website.com", "pathPrefix": ["/open"] },
201 |         { "host": "another.site.br" }
202 |       ],
203 |       "desktop": {
204 |         "schemes": ["something", "my-tauri-app"]
205 |       }
206 |     }
207 |   }
208 | }
209 | ```
210 | 
211 | With the above configuration, the `something://*` and `my-tauri-app://*` URLs are associated with your desktop application,
212 | and on mobile the `https://another.site.br/*` and `https://your.website.com/open/*` URLs will open your mobile app.
213 | 
214 | ## Usage
215 | 
216 | The deep-link plugin is available in both JavaScript and Rust.
217 | 
218 | ### Listening to Deep Links
219 | 
220 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
221 |   <TabItem label="JavaScript">
222 | 
223 | When a deep link triggers your app to be opened, the `onOpenUrl` callback is executed:
224 | 
225 | ```javascript
226 | import { onOpenUrl } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-deep-link';
227 | // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
228 | // const { onOpenUrl } = window.__TAURI__.deepLink;
229 | 
230 | await onOpenUrl((urls) => {
231 |   console.log('deep link:', urls);
232 | });
233 | ```
234 | 
235 |   </TabItem>
236 |   <TabItem label="Rust">
237 | 
238 | When a deep link triggers your app to be opened, the `on_open_url` closure is called:
239 | 
240 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs"
241 | use tauri_plugin_deep_link::DeepLinkExt;
242 | 
243 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
244 | pub fn run() {
245 |     tauri::Builder::default()
246 |         .plugin(tauri_plugin_deep_link::init())
247 |         .setup(|app| {
248 |             app.deep_link().on_open_url(|event| {
249 |                 println!("deep link URLs: {:?}", event.urls());
250 |             });
251 |             Ok(())
252 |         })
253 |         .run(tauri::generate_context!())
254 |         .expect("error while running tauri application");
255 | }
256 | ```
257 | 
258 |   </TabItem>
259 | </Tabs>
260 | 
261 | :::note
262 | The open URL event is triggered with a list of URLs that were requested to be compatible with the macOS API for deep links,
263 | but in most cases your app will only receive a single URL.
264 | :::
265 | 
266 | ### Registering Desktop Deep Links at Runtime
267 | 
268 | The [configuration](#configuration) section describes how to define static deep link schemes for your application.
269 | 
270 | On Linux and Windows it is possible to also associate schemes with your application at runtime via the `register` Rust function.
271 | 
272 | In the following snippet, we will register the `my-app` scheme at runtime. After executing the app for the first time,
273 | the operating system will open `my-app://*` URLs with our application:
274 | 
275 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs"
276 | use tauri_plugin_deep_link::DeepLinkExt;
277 | 
278 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
279 | pub fn run() {
280 |     tauri::Builder::default()
281 |         .plugin(tauri_plugin_deep_link::init())
282 |         .setup(|app| {
283 |             #[cfg(desktop)]
284 |             app.deep_link().register("my-app")?;
285 |             Ok(())
286 |         })
287 |         .run(tauri::generate_context!())
288 |         .expect("error while running tauri application");
289 | }
290 | ```
291 | 
292 | :::note
293 | Registering the deep links at runtime can be useful for developing on Linux and Windows
294 | as by default the deep link is only registered when your app is installed.
295 | 
296 | Installing an AppImage can be complicated as it requires an AppImage launcher.
297 | 
298 | Registering the deep links at runtime might be preferred, so Tauri also includes a
299 | helper function to force register all statically configured deep links at runtime.
300 | Calling this function also ensures the deep links is registered for development mode:
301 | 
302 | ```rust
303 | #[cfg(any(target_os = "linux", all(debug_assertions, windows)))]
304 | {
305 |   use tauri_plugin_deep_link::DeepLinkExt;
306 |   app.deep_link().register_all()?;
307 | }
308 | ```
309 | 
310 | :::
311 | 
312 | ## Testing
313 | 
314 | There are some caveats to test deep links for your application.
315 | 
316 | ### Desktop
317 | 
318 | Deep links are only triggered for installed applications on desktop.
319 | On Linux and Windows you can circumvent this using the [`register_all`] Rust function,
320 | which registers all configured schemes to trigger the current executable:
321 | 
322 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs"
323 | use tauri_plugin_deep_link::DeepLinkExt;
324 | 
325 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
326 | pub fn run() {
327 |     tauri::Builder::default()
328 |         .plugin(tauri_plugin_deep_link::init())
329 |         .setup(|app| {
330 |             #[cfg(any(windows, target_os = "linux"))]
331 |             {
332 |                 use tauri_plugin_deep_link::DeepLinkExt;
333 |                 app.deep_link().register_all()?;
334 |             }
335 |             Ok(())
336 |         })
337 |         .run(tauri::generate_context!())
338 |         .expect("error while running tauri application");
339 | }
340 | ```
341 | 
342 | :::note
343 | Installing an AppImage that supports deep links on Linux requires an AppImage launcher to integrate the AppImage with the operating system.
344 | Using the `register_all` function you can support deep links out of the box, without requiring your users to use external tools.
345 | 
346 | When the AppImage is moved to a different location in the file system, the deep link is invalidated since it leverages an absolute path
347 | to the executable, which makes registering the schemes at runtime even more important.
348 | 
349 | See the [Registering Desktop Deep Links at Runtime](#registering-desktop-deep-links-at-runtime) section for more information.
350 | :::
351 | 
352 | :::caution
353 | Registering deep links at runtime is not possible on macOS, so deep links can only be tested on the bundled application,
354 | which must be installed in the `/Applications` directory.
355 | :::
356 | 
357 | #### Windows
358 | 
359 | To trigger a deep link on Windows you can either open `<scheme>://url` in the browser or run the following command in the terminal:
360 | 
361 | ```sh
362 | start <scheme>://url
363 | ```
364 | 
365 | #### Linux
366 | 
367 | To trigger a deep link on Linux you can either open `<scheme>://url` in the browser or run `xdg-open` in the terminal:
368 | 
369 | ```sh
370 | xdg-open <scheme>://url
371 | ```
372 | 
373 | ### iOS
374 | 
375 | To trigger an app link on iOS you can open the `https://<host>/path` URL in the browser. For simulators you can leverage the `simctl` CLI to directly open a link from the terminal:
376 | 
377 | ```sh
378 | xcrun simctl openurl booted https://<host>/path
379 | ```
380 | 
381 | ### Android
382 | 
383 | To trigger an app link on Android you can open the `https://<host>/path` URL in the browser. For emulators you can leverage the `adb` CLI to directly open a link from the terminal:
