119 | ## Usage
120 | 
121 | The fs plugin is available in both JavaScript and Rust.
122 | 
123 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
124 |   <TabItem label="JavaScript" >
125 | 
126 | ```javascript
127 | import { exists, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
128 | // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
129 | // const { exists, BaseDirectory } = window.__TAURI__.fs;
130 | 
131 | // Check if the `$APPDATA/avatar.png` file exists
132 | await exists('avatar.png', { baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData });
133 | ```
134 | 
135 |   </TabItem>
136 |   <TabItem label = "Rust" >
137 | 
138 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs"
139 | use tauri_plugin_fs::FsExt;
140 | 
141 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
142 | pub fn run() {
143 |   tauri::Builder::default()
144 |       .plugin(tauri_plugin_fs::init())
145 |       .setup(|app| {
146 |           // allowed the given directory
147 |           let scope = app.fs_scope();
148 |         	scope.allow_directory("/path/to/directory", false);
149 |           dbg!(scope.allowed());
150 | 
151 |           Ok(())
152 |        })
153 |        .run(tauri::generate_context!())
154 |        .expect("error while running tauri application");
155 | }
156 | ```
157 | 
158 |   </TabItem>
159 | </Tabs>
160 | 
161 | ## Security
162 | 
163 | This module prevents path traversal, not allowing parent directory accessors to be used
164 | (i.e. "/usr/path/to/../file" or "../path/to/file" paths are not allowed).
165 | Paths accessed with this API must be either relative to one of the [base directories][base directory]
166 | or created with the [path API].
167 | 
168 | See [@tauri-apps/plugin-fs - Security] for more information.
169 | 
170 | ## Paths
171 | 
172 | The file system plugin offers two ways of manipulating paths: the [base directory] and the [path API].
173 | 
174 | - base directory
175 | 
176 |   Every API has an options argument that lets you define a [baseDir][base directory] that acts as the working directory of the operation.
177 | 
178 |   ```js
179 |   import { readFile } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
180 |   const contents = await readFile('avatars/tauri.png', {
181 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.Home,
182 |   });
183 |   ```
184 | 
185 |   In the above example the ~/avatars/tauri.png file is read since we are using the **Home** base directory.
186 | 
187 | - path API
188 | 
189 |   Alternatively you can use the path APIs to perform path manipulations.
190 | 
191 |   ```js
192 |   import { readFile } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
193 |   import * as path from '@tauri-apps/api/path';
194 |   const home = await path.homeDir();
195 |   const contents = await readFile(await path.join(home, 'avatars/tauri.png'));
196 |   ```
197 | 
198 | ## Files
199 | 
200 | ### Create
201 | 
202 | Creates a file and returns a handle to it. If the file already exists, it is truncated.
203 | 
204 | ```js
205 | import { create, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
206 | const file = await create('foo/bar.txt', { baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData });
207 | await file.write(new TextEncoder().encode('Hello world'));
208 | await file.close();
209 | ```
210 | 
211 | :::note
212 | Always call `file.close()` when you are done manipulating the file.
213 | :::
214 | 
215 | ### Write
216 | 
217 | The plugin offers separate APIs for writing text and binary files for performance.
218 | 
219 | - text files
220 | 
221 |   ```js
222 |   import { writeTextFile, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
223 |   const contents = JSON.stringify({ notifications: true });
224 |   await writeTextFile('config.json', contents, {
225 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppConfig,
226 |   });
227 |   ```
228 | 
229 | - binary files
230 | 
231 |   ```js
232 |   import { writeFile, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
233 |   const contents = new Uint8Array(); // fill a byte array
234 |   await writeFile('config', contents, {
235 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppConfig,
236 |   });
237 |   ```
238 | 
239 | ### Open
240 | 
241 | Opens a file and returns a handle to it.
242 | With this API you have more control over how the file should be opened
243 | (read-only mode, write-only mode, append instead of overwrite, only create if it does not exist, etc).
244 | 
245 | :::note
246 | Always call `file.close()` when you are done manipulating the file.
247 | :::
248 | 
249 | - read-only
250 | 
251 |   This is the default mode.
252 | 
253 |   ```js
254 |   import { open, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
255 |   const file = await open('foo/bar.txt', {
256 |     read: true,
257 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData,
258 |   });
259 |   const buf = new Uint8Array();
260 |   await file.read(buf);
261 |   const textContents = new TextDecoder().decode(buf);
262 |   await file.close();
263 |   ```
264 | 
265 | - write-only
266 | 
267 |   ```js
268 |   import { open, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
269 |   const file = await open('foo/bar.txt', {
270 |     write: true,
271 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData,
272 |   });
273 |   await file.write(new TextEncoder().encode('Hello world'));
274 |   await file.close();
275 |   ```
276 | 
277 |   By default the file is truncated on any `file.write()` call.
278 |   See the following example to learn how to append to the existing contents instead.
279 | 
280 | - append
281 | 
282 |   ```js
283 |   import { open, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
284 |   const file = await open('foo/bar.txt', {
285 |     append: true,
286 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData,
287 |   });
288 |   await file.write(new TextEncoder().encode('world'));
289 |   await file.close();
290 |   ```
291 | 
292 |   Note that `{ append: true }` has the same effect as `{ write: true, append: true }`.
293 | 
294 | - truncate
295 | 
296 |   When the `truncate` option is set and the file already exists, it will be truncated to length 0.
297 | 
298 |   ```js
299 |   import { open, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
300 |   const file = await open('foo/bar.txt', {
301 |     write: true,
302 |     truncate: true,
303 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData,
304 |   });
305 |   await file.write(new TextEncoder().encode('world'));
306 |   await file.close();
307 |   ```
308 | 
309 |   This option requires `write` to be `true`.
310 | 
311 |   You can use it along the `append` option if you want to rewrite an existing file using multiple `file.write()` calls.
312 | 
313 | - create
314 | 
315 |   By default the `open` API only opens existing files. To create the file if it does not exist,
316 |   opening it if it does, set `create` to `true`:
317 | 
318 |   ```js
319 |   import { open, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
320 |   const file = await open('foo/bar.txt', {
321 |     write: true,
322 |     create: true,
323 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData,
324 |   });
325 |   await file.write(new TextEncoder().encode('world'));
326 |   await file.close();
327 |   ```
328 | 
329 |   In order for the file to be created, `write` or `append` must also be set to `true`.
330 | 
331 |   To fail if the file already exists, see `createNew`.
332 | 
333 | - createNew
334 | 
335 |   `createNew` works similarly to `create`, but if the file does not exist, the operation fails.
336 | 
337 |   ```js
338 |   import { open, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
339 |   const file = await open('foo/bar.txt', {
340 |     write: true,
341 |     createNew: true,
342 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppData,
343 |   });
344 |   await file.write(new TextEncoder().encode('world'));
345 |   await file.close();
346 |   ```
347 | 
348 |   In order for the file to be created, `write` must also be set to `true`.
349 | 
350 | ### Read
351 | 
352 | The plugin offers separate APIs for reading text and binary files for performance.
353 | 
354 | - text files
355 | 
356 |   ```js
357 |   import { readTextFile, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
358 |   const configToml = await readTextFile('config.toml', {
359 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppConfig,
360 |   });
361 |   ```
362 | 
363 |   If the file is large you can stream its lines with the `readTextFileLines` API:
364 | 
365 |   ```typescript
366 |   import { readTextFileLines, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
367 |   const lines = await readTextFileLines('app.logs', {
368 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLog,
369 |   });
370 |   for await (const line of lines) {
371 |     console.log(line);
372 |   }
373 |   ```
374 | 
375 | - binary files
376 | 
377 |   ```js
378 |   import { readFile, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
379 |   const icon = await readFile('icon.png', {
380 |     baseDir: BaseDirectory.Resources,
381 |   });
382 |   ```
383 | 
384 | ### Remove
385 | 
386 | Call `remove()` to delete a file. If the file does not exist, an error is returned.
387 | 
388 | ```js
389 | import { remove, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
390 | await remove('user.db', { baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData });
391 | ```
392 | 
393 | ### Copy
394 | 
395 | The `copyFile` function takes the source and destination paths.
396 | Note that you must configure each base directory separately.
397 | 
398 | ```js
399 | import { copyFile, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
400 | await copyFile('user.db', 'user.db.bk', {
401 |   fromPathBaseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
402 |   toPathBaseDir: BaseDirectory.Temp,
403 | });
404 | ```
405 | 
406 | In the above example the \<app-local-data\>/user.db file is copied to $TMPDIR/user.db.bk.
407 | 
408 | ### Exists
409 | 
410 | Use the `exists()` function to check if a file exists:
411 | 
412 | ```js
413 | import { exists, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
414 | const tokenExists = await exists('token', {
415 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
416 | });
417 | ```
418 | 
419 | ### Metadata
420 | 
421 | File metadata can be retrieved with the `stat` and the `lstat` functions.
422 | `stat` follows symlinks (and returns an error if the actual file it points to is not allowed by the scope)
423 | and `lstat` does not follow symlinks, returning the information of the symlink itself.
424 | 
425 | ```js
426 | import { stat, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
427 | const metadata = await stat('app.db', {
428 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
429 | });
430 | ```
431 | 
432 | ### Rename
433 | 
434 | The `rename` function takes the source and destination paths.
435 | Note that you must configure each base directory separately.
436 | 
437 | ```js
438 | import { rename, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
439 | await rename('user.db.bk', 'user.db', {
440 |   fromPathBaseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
441 |   toPathBaseDir: BaseDirectory.Temp,
442 | });
443 | ```
444 | 
445 | In the above example the \<app-local-data\>/user.db.bk file is renamed to $TMPDIR/user.db.
446 | 
447 | ### Truncate
448 | 
449 | Truncates or extends the specified file to reach the specified file length (defaults to 0).
450 | 
451 | - truncate to 0 length
452 | 
453 | ```typescript
454 | import { truncate } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
455 | await truncate('my_file.txt', 0, { baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData });
456 | ```
457 | 
458 | - truncate to a specific length
459 | 
460 | ```typescript
461 | import {
462 |   truncate,
463 |   readTextFile,
464 |   writeTextFile,
465 |   BaseDirectory,
466 | } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
467 | 
468 | const filePath = 'file.txt';
469 | await writeTextFile(filePath, 'Hello World', {
470 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
471 | });
472 | await truncate(filePath, 7, {
473 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
474 | });
475 | const data = await readTextFile(filePath, {
476 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
477 | });
478 | console.log(data); // "Hello W"
479 | ```
480 | 
481 | ## Directories
482 | 
483 | ### Create
484 | 
485 | To create a directory, call the `mkdir` function:
486 | 
487 | ```js
488 | import { mkdir, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
489 | await mkdir('images', {
490 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
491 | });
492 | ```
493 | 
494 | ### Read
495 | 
496 | The `readDir` function recursively lists the entries of a directory:
497 | 
498 | ```typescript
499 | import { readDir, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
500 | const entries = await readDir('users', { baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData });
501 | ```
502 | 
503 | ### Remove
504 | 
505 | Call `remove()` to delete a directory. If the directory does not exist, an error is returned.
506 | 
507 | ```js
508 | import { remove, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
509 | await remove('images', { baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData });
510 | ```
511 | 
512 | If the directory is not empty, the `recursive` option must be set to `true`:
513 | 
514 | ```js
515 | import { remove, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
516 | await remove('images', {
517 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
518 |   recursive: true,
519 | });
520 | ```
521 | 
522 | ### Exists
523 | 
524 | Use the `exists()` function to check if a directory exists:
525 | 
526 | ```js
527 | import { exists, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
528 | const tokenExists = await exists('images', {
529 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
530 | });
531 | ```
532 | 
533 | ### Metadata
534 | 
535 | Directory metadata can be retrieved with the `stat` and the `lstat` functions.
536 | `stat` follows symlinks (and returns an error if the actual file it points to is not allowed by the scope)
537 | and `lstat` does not follow symlinks, returning the information of the symlink itself.
538 | 
539 | ```js
540 | import { stat, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
541 | const metadata = await stat('databases', {
542 |   baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLocalData,
543 | });
544 | ```
545 | 
546 | ## Watching changes
547 | 
548 | To watch a directory or file for changes, use the `watch` or `watchImmediate` functions.
549 | 
550 | - watch
551 | 
552 |   `watch` is debounced so it only emits events after a certain delay:
553 | 
554 |   ```js
555 |   import { watch, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
556 |   await watch(
557 |     'app.log',
558 |     (event) => {
559 |       console.log('app.log event', event);
560 |     },
561 |     {
562 |       baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLog,
563 |       delayMs: 500,
564 |     }
565 |   );
566 |   ```
567 | 
568 | - watchImmediate
569 | 
570 |   `watchImmediate` immediately notifies listeners of an event:
571 | 
572 |   ```js
573 |   import { watchImmediate, BaseDirectory } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-fs';
574 |   await watchImmediate(
575 |     'logs',
576 |     (event) => {
577 |       console.log('logs directory event', event);
578 |     },
579 |     {
580 |       baseDir: BaseDirectory.AppLog,
581 |       recursive: true,
582 |     }
583 |   );
584 |   ```
585 | 
586 | By default watch operations on a directory are not recursive.
587 | Set the `recursive` option to `true` to recursively watch for changes on all sub-directories.
588 | 
589 | :::note
590 | The watch functions require the `watch` feature flag:
591 | 
592 | ```toml title="src-tauri/Cargo.toml"
593 | [dependencies]
594 | tauri-plugin-fs = { version = "2.0.0", features = ["watch"] }
595 | ```
596 | 
597 | :::
598 | 
599 | ## Permissions
600 | 
601 | By default all potentially dangerous plugin commands and scopes are blocked and cannot be accessed. You must modify the permissions in your `capabilities` configuration to enable these.
602 | 
603 | See the [Capabilities Overview](/security/capabilities/) for more information and the [step by step guide](/learn/security/using-plugin-permissions/) to use plugin permissions.
604 | 
605 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" ins={7-11}
606 | {
607 |   "$schema": "../gen/schemas/desktop-schema.json",
608 |   "identifier": "main-capability",
609 |   "description": "Capability for the main window",
610 |   "windows": ["main"],
611 |   "permissions": [
612 |     "fs:default",
613 |     {
614 |       "identifier": "fs:allow-exists",
615 |       "allow": [{ "path": "$APPDATA/*" }]
616 |     }
617 |   ]
618 | }
619 | ```
620 | 
621 | <PluginPermissions plugin={frontmatter.plugin} />
622 | 
623 | ### Scopes
624 | 
625 | This plugin permissions includes scopes for defining which paths are allowed or explicitly rejected.
626 | For more information on scopes, see the [Command Scopes].
627 | 
628 | Each `allow` or `deny` scope must include an array listing all paths that should be allowed or denied.
629 | The scope entries are in the `{ path: string }` format.
630 | 
631 | :::note
632 | `deny` take precedence over `allow` so if a path is denied by a scope, it will be blocked at runtime
633 | even if it is allowed by another scope.
634 | :::
635 | 
636 | Scope entries can use `
lt;path>` variables to reference common system paths such as the home directory,
637 | the app resources directory and the config directory. The following table lists all common paths you can reference:
638 | 
639 | | Path                                                                                            | Variable      |
640 | | ----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------- |
641 | | [appConfigDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#appconfigdir)       | $APPCONFIG    |
642 | | [appDataDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#appdatadir)           | $APPDATA      |
643 | | [appLocalDataDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#appLocaldatadir) | $APPLOCALDATA |
644 | | [appcacheDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#appcachedir)         | $APPCACHE     |
645 | | [applogDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#applogdir)             | $APPLOG       |
646 | | [audioDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#audiodir)               | $AUDIO        |
647 | | [cacheDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#cachedir)               | $CACHE        |
648 | | [configDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#configdir)             | $CONFIG       |
649 | | [dataDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#datadir)                 | $DATA         |
650 | | [localDataDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#localdatadir)       | $LOCALDATA    |
651 | | [desktopDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#desktopdir)           | $DESKTOP      |
652 | | [documentDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#documentdir)         | $DOCUMENT     |
653 | | [downloadDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#downloaddir)         | $DOWNLOAD     |
654 | | [executableDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#executabledir)     | $EXE          |
655 | | [fontDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#fontdir)                 | $FONT         |
656 | | [homeDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#homedir)                 | $HOME         |
657 | | [pictureDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#picturedir)           | $PICTURE      |
658 | | [publicDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#publicdir)             | $PUBLIC       |
659 | | [runtimeDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#runtimedir)           | $RUNTIME      |
660 | | [templateDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#templatedir)         | $TEMPLATE     |
661 | | [videoDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#videodir)               | $VIDEO        |
662 | | [resourceDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#resourcedir)         | $RESOURCE     |
663 | | [tempDir](https://v2.tauri.app/reference/javascript/api/namespacepath/#tempdir)                 | $TEMP         |
664 | 
665 | #### Examples
666 | 
667 | - global scope
668 | 
669 | To apply a scope to any `fs` command, use the `fs:scope` permission:
670 | 
671 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" {7-10}
672 | {
673 |   "$schema": "../gen/schemas/desktop-schema.json",
674 |   "identifier": "main-capability",
675 |   "description": "Capability for the main window",
676 |   "windows": ["main"],
677 |   "permissions": [
678 |     {
679 |       "identifier": "fs:scope",
680 |       "allow": [{ "path": "$APPDATA" }, { "path": "$APPDATA/**" }]
681 |     }
682 |   ]
683 | }
684 | ```
685 | 
686 | To apply a scope to a specific `fs` command,
687 | use the the object form of permissions `{ "identifier": string, "allow"?: [], "deny"?: [] }`:
688 | 
689 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" {7-18}
690 | {
691 |   "$schema": "../gen/schemas/desktop-schema.json",
692 |   "identifier": "main-capability",
693 |   "description": "Capability for the main window",
694 |   "windows": ["main"],
695 |   "permissions": [
696 |     {
697 |       "identifier": "fs:allow-rename",
698 |       "allow": [{ "path": "$HOME/**" }]
699 |     },
700 |     {
701 |       "identifier": "fs:allow-rename",
702 |       "deny": [{ "path": "$HOME/.config/**" }]
703 |     },
704 |     {
705 |       "identifier": "fs:allow-exists",
706 |       "allow": [{ "path": "$APPDATA/*" }]
707 |     }
708 |   ]
709 | }
710 | ```
711 | 
712 | In the above example you can use the [`exists`](#exists) API using any `$APPDATA` sub path (does not include sub-directories)
713 | and the [`rename`](#rename)
714 | 
715 | :::tip
716 | If you are trying to access dotfiles (e.g. `.gitignore`) or dotfolders (e.g. `.ssh`) on Unix based systems,
717 | then you need to specify either the full path `/home/user/.ssh/example` or the glob after the dotfolder path
718 | component `/home/user/.ssh/*`.
719 | 
720 | If that does not work in your use case then you can configure the plugin to treat any component
721 | as a valid path literal.
722 | 
723 | ```json title="src-tauri/tauri.conf.json
724 |  "plugins": {
725 |     "fs": {
726 |       "requireLiteralLeadingDot": false
727 |     }
728 |   }
729 | ```
730 | 
