 71 |           bun = "bun add @tauri-apps/plugin-log"
 72 |         />
 73 | 
 74 |     </Steps>
 75 | 
 76 |   </TabItem>
 77 | </Tabs>
 78 | 
 79 | ## Usage
 80 | 
 81 |   <Steps>
 82 | 
 83 | 1.  First, you need to register the plugin with Tauri.
 84 | 
 85 |     ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs" {1} {6-14}
 86 |     use tauri_plugin_log::{Target, TargetKind};
 87 | 
 88 |     #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
 89 |     pub fn run() {
 90 |         tauri::Builder::default()
 91 |             .plugin(tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new().build())
 92 |             .run(tauri::generate_context!())
 93 |             .expect("error while running tauri application");
 94 |     }
 95 |     ```
 96 | 
 97 | 2.  Afterwards, all the plugin's APIs are available through the JavaScript guest bindings:
 98 | 
 99 |     ```javascript
100 |     import {
101 |       warn,
102 |       debug,
103 |       trace,
104 |       info,
105 |       error,
106 |       attachConsole,
107 |       attachLogger,
108 |     } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-log';
109 |     // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
110 |     // const { warn, debug, trace, info, error, attachConsole, attachLogger } = window.__TAURI__.log;
111 |     ```
112 | 
113 |   </Steps>
114 | 
115 | ## Logging
116 | 
117 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
118 |   <TabItem label="JavaScript">
119 | Use one of the plugin's `warn`, `debug`, `trace`, `info` or  `error` APIs to produce a log record from JavaScript code:
120 | 
121 | ```js
122 | import { warn, debug, trace, info, error } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-log';
123 | 
124 | trace('Trace');
125 | info('Info');
126 | error('Error');
127 | ```
128 | 
129 | To automatically forward all `console` messages to the log plugin you can rewrite them:
130 | 
131 | ```ts
132 | import { warn, debug, trace, info, error } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-log';
133 | 
134 | function forwardConsole(
135 |   fnName: 'log' | 'debug' | 'info' | 'warn' | 'error',
136 |   logger: (message: string) => Promise<void>
137 | ) {
138 |   const original = console[fnName];
139 |   console[fnName] = (message) => {
140 |     original(message);
141 |     logger(message);
142 |   };
143 | }
144 | 
145 | forwardConsole('log', trace);
146 | forwardConsole('debug', debug);
147 | forwardConsole('info', info);
148 | forwardConsole('warn', warn);
149 | forwardConsole('error', error);
150 | ```
151 | 
152 | </TabItem>
153 | 
154 | <TabItem label="Rust">
155 | To create your own logs on the Rust side you can use the [`log` crate]:
156 | 
157 | ```rust
158 | log::error!("something bad happened!");
159 | log::info!("Tauri is awesome!");
160 | ```
161 | 
162 | Note that the [`log` crate] must be added to your `Cargo.toml` file:
163 | 
164 | ```toml
165 | [dependencies]
166 | log = "0.4"
167 | ```
168 | 
169 | </TabItem>
170 | </Tabs>
171 | 
172 | ## Log targets
173 | 
174 | The log plugin builder has a `targets` function that lets you configure common destination of all your application logs.
175 | 
176 | :::note
177 | By default the plugin logs to stdout and to a file in the application logs directory.
178 | To only use your own log targets, call `clear_targets`:
179 | 
180 | ```rust
181 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
182 | .clear_targets()
183 | .build()
184 | ```
185 | 
186 | :::
187 | 
188 | ### Printing logs to the terminal
189 | 
190 | To forward all your logs to the terminal, enable the `Stdout` or `Stderr` targets:
191 | 
192 | ```rust
193 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
194 |   .target(tauri_plugin_log::Target::new(
195 |     tauri_plugin_log::TargetKind::Stdout,
196 |   ))
197 |   .build()
198 | ```
199 | 
200 | This target is enabled by default.
201 | 
202 | ### Logging to the webview console
203 | 
204 | To view all your Rust logs in the webview console, enable the `Webview` target and run `attachConsole` in your frontend:
205 | 
206 | ```rust
207 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
208 |   .target(tauri_plugin_log::Target::new(
209 |     tauri_plugin_log::TargetKind::Webview,
210 |   ))
211 |   .build()
212 | ```
213 | 
214 | ```js
215 | import { attachConsole } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-log';
216 | const detach = await attachConsole();
217 | // call detach() if you do not want to print logs to the console anymore
218 | ```
219 | 
220 | ### Persisting logs
221 | 
222 | To write all logs to a file, you can use either the `LogDir` or the `Folder` targets.
223 | 
224 | - `LogDir`:
225 | 
226 | ```rust
227 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
228 |   .target(tauri_plugin_log::Target::new(
229 |     tauri_plugin_log::TargetKind::LogDir {
230 |       file_name: Some("logs".to_string()),
231 |     },
232 |   ))
233 |   .build()
234 | ```
235 | 
236 | When using the LogDir target, all logs are stored in the recommended log directory.
237 | The following table describes the location of the logs per platform:
238 | 
239 | | Platform | Value                                             | Example                                           |
240 | | -------- | ------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------- |
241 | | Linux    | `{configDir}/{bundleIdentifier}`                  | `/home/alice/.config/com.tauri.dev`               |
242 | | macOS    | `{homeDir}/Library/Logs/{bundleIdentifier}`       | `/Users/Alice/Library/Logs/com.tauri.dev`         |
243 | | Windows  | `{FOLDERID_LocalAppData}/{bundleIdentifier}/logs` | `C:\Users\Alice\AppData\Local\com.tauri.dev\logs` |
244 | 
245 | - `Folder`:
246 | 
247 | The Folder target lets you write logs to a custom location in the filesystem.
248 | 
249 | ```rust
250 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
251 |   .target(tauri_plugin_log::Target::new(
252 |     tauri_plugin_log::TargetKind::Folder {
253 |       path: std::path::PathBuf::from("/path/to/logs"),
254 |       file_name: None,
255 |     },
256 |   ))
257 |   .build()
258 | ```
259 | 
260 | The default `file_name` is the application name.
261 | 
262 | #### Configuring log file behavior
263 | 
264 | By default the log file gets discarded when it reaches the maximum size.
265 | The maximum file size can be configured via the builder's `max_file_size` function:
266 | 
267 | ```rust
268 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
269 |   .max_file_size(50_000 /* bytes */)
270 |   .build()
271 | ```
272 | 
273 | Tauri can automatically rotate your log file when it reaches the size limit instead of discarding the previous file.
274 | This behavior can be configured using `rotation_strategy`:
275 | 
276 | ```rust
277 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
278 |   .rotation_strategy(tauri_plugin_log::RotationStrategy::KeepAll)
279 |   .build()
280 | ```
281 | 
282 | ### Filtering
283 | 
284 | By default **all** logs are processed. There are some mechanisms to reduce the amount of logs and filter only relevant information.
285 | 
286 | ### Maximum log level
287 | 
288 | To set a maximum log level, use the `level` function:
289 | 
290 | ```rust
291 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
292 |   .level(log::LevelFilter::Info)
293 |   .build()
294 | ```
295 | 
296 | In this example, debug and trace logs are discarded as they have a lower level than _info_.
297 | 
298 | It is also possible to define separate maximum levels for individual modules:
299 | 
300 | ```rust
301 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
302 |   .level(log::LevelFilter::Info)
303 |   // verbose logs only for the commands module
304 |   .level_for("my_crate_name::commands", log::LevelFilter::Trace)
305 |   .build()
306 | ```
307 | 
308 | Note that these APIs use the [`log` crate], which must be added to your `Cargo.toml` file:
309 | 
310 | ```toml
311 | [dependencies]
312 | log = "0.4"
313 | ```
314 | 
315 | ### Target filter
316 | 
317 | A `filter` function can be defined to discard unwanted logs by checking their metadata:
318 | 
319 | ```rust
320 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
321 |   // exclude logs with target `"hyper"`
322 |   .filter(|metadata| metadata.target() != "hyper")
323 |   .build()
324 | ```
325 | 
326 | ### Formatting
327 | 
328 | The log plugin formats each log record as `DATE[TARGET][LEVEL] MESSAGE`.
329 | A custom format function can be provided with `format`:
330 | 
331 | ```rust
332 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
333 |   .format(|out, message, record| {
334 |     out.finish(format_args!(
335 |       "[{} {}] {}",
336 |       record.level(),
337 |       record.target(),
338 |       message
339 |     ))
340 |   })
341 |   .build()
342 | ```
343 | 
344 | #### Log dates
345 | 
346 | By default the log plugin uses the UTC timezone to format dates
347 | but you can configure it to use the local timezone with `timezone_strategy`:
348 | 
349 | ```rust
350 | tauri_plugin_log::Builder::new()
351 |   .timezone_strategy(tauri_plugin_log::TimezoneStrategy::UseLocal)
352 |   .build()
353 | ```
354 | 
355 | ## Permissions
356 | 
357 | By default, all plugin commands are blocked and cannot be accessed.
358 | You must define a list of permissions in your `capabilities` configuration.
359 | 
360 | See the [Capabilities Overview](/security/capabilities/) for more information and the [step by step guide](/learn/security/using-plugin-permissions/) to use plugin permissions.
361 | 
362 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" ins={6}
363 | {
364 |   "$schema": "../gen/schemas/desktop-schema.json",
365 |   "identifier": "main-capability",
366 |   "description": "Capability for the main window",
367 |   "windows": ["main"],
368 |   "permissions": ["log:default"]
369 | }
370 | ```
371 | 
372 | <PluginPermissions plugin={frontmatter.plugin} />
