 84 | 
 85 | ## Configuration
 86 | 
 87 | The NFC plugin requires native configuration for iOS.
 88 | 
 89 | ### iOS
 90 | 
 91 | To access the NFC APIs on iOS you must configure a usage description on the Info.plist file and add the NFC capability to your application.
 92 | 
 93 | #### Info.plist
 94 | 
 95 | On iOS the NFC plugin requires the `NFCReaderUsageDescription` information property list value, which should describe why your app needs to scan or write to NFC tags.
 96 | 
 97 | In the `src-tauri/Info.ios.plist` file, add the following snippet:
 98 | 
 99 | ```xml title=src-tauri/Info.ios.plist
100 | <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
101 | <!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
102 | <plist version="1.0">
103 | 	<dict>
104 | 		<key>NFCReaderUsageDescription</key>
105 | 		<string>Read and write various NFC tags</string>
106 | 	</dict>
107 | </plist>
108 | ```
109 | 
110 | #### NFC Capability
111 | 
112 | Additionally iOS requires the NFC capability to be associated with your application.
113 | 
114 | The capability can be added in Xcode in the project configuration's "Signing & Capabilities" tab by clicking the "+ Capability" button and
115 | selecting the "Near Field Communication Tag Reading" capability (see [Add a capability to a target] for more information)
116 | or by adding the following configuration to the `gen/apple/<app-name>_iOS/<app-name>_iOS.entitlements` file:
117 | 
118 | ```xml title="gen/apple/<app-name>_iOS/<app-name>_iOS.entitlements"
119 | <?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
120 | <!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
121 | <plist version="1.0">
122 | <dict>
123 | 	<key>com.apple.developer.nfc.readersession.formats</key>
124 | 	<array>
125 | 		<string>TAG</string>
126 | 	</array>
127 | </dict>
128 | </plist>
129 | ```
130 | 
131 | ## Usage
132 | 
133 | The NFC plugin is available in both JavaScript and Rust, allowing you to scan and write to NFC tags.
134 | 
135 | ### Checking if NFC is supported
136 | 
137 | Not every mobile device has the capability to scan NFC tags, so you should check for availability before using the scan and write APIs.
138 | 
139 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
140 | 
141 | <TabItem label="JavaScript">
142 | 
143 | ```javascript
144 | import { isAvailable } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-nfc';
145 | 
146 | const canScanNfc = await isAvailable();
147 | ```
148 | 
149 | </TabItem>
150 | <TabItem label="Rust">
151 | 
152 | ```rust
153 | tauri::Builder::default()
154 |   .setup(|app| {
155 |     #[cfg(mobile)]
156 |     {
157 |       use tauri_plugin_nfc::NfcExt;
158 | 
159 |       app.handle().plugin(tauri_plugin_nfc::init());
160 | 
161 |       let can_scan_nfc = app.nfc().is_available()?;
162 |     }
163 |     Ok(())
164 |   })
165 | ```
166 | 
167 | </TabItem>
168 | </Tabs>
169 | 
170 | ### Scanning NFC tags
171 | 
172 | The plugin can scan either generic NFC tags or NFC tags with a NDEF (NFC Data Exchange Format) message,
173 | which is a standard format to encapsulate typed data in an NFC tag.
174 | 
175 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
176 | 
177 | <TabItem label="JavaScript">
178 | 
179 | ```javascript
180 | import { scan } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-nfc';
181 | 
182 | const scanType = {
183 |   type: 'ndef', // or 'tag',
184 | };
185 | 
186 | const options = {
187 |   keepSessionAlive: false,
188 |   // configure the messages displayed in the "Scan NFC" dialog on iOS
189 |   message: 'Scan a NFC tag',
190 |   successMessage: 'NFC tag successfully scanned',
191 | };
192 | 
193 | const tag = await scan(scanType, options);
194 | ```
195 | 
196 | </TabItem>
197 | 
198 | <TabItem label="Rust">
199 | 
200 | ```rust
201 | tauri::Builder::default()
202 |   .setup(|app| {
203 |     #[cfg(mobile)]
204 |     {
205 |       use tauri_plugin_nfc::NfcExt;
206 | 
207 |       app.handle().plugin(tauri_plugin_nfc::init());
208 | 
209 |       let tag = app
210 |         .nfc()
211 |         .scan(tauri_plugin_nfc::ScanRequest {
212 |             kind: tauri_plugin_nfc::ScanKind::Ndef {
213 |                 mime_type: None,
214 |                 uri: None,
215 |                 tech_list: None,
216 |             },
217 |             keep_session_alive: false,
218 |         })?
219 |         .tag;
220 |     }
221 |     Ok(())
222 |   })
223 | ```
224 | 
225 | </TabItem>
226 | 
227 | </Tabs>
228 | 
229 | :::note
230 | The `keepSessionAlive` option can be used to directly write to the scanned NFC tag later.
231 | 
232 | If you do not provide that option, the session is recreated on the next `write()` call,
233 | which means the app will try to rescan the tag.
234 | :::
235 | 
236 | #### Filters
237 | 
238 | The NFC scanner can also filter tags with a specific URI format, mime type or NFC tag technologies.
239 | In this case, the scan will only detect tags that matches the provided filters.
240 | 
241 | :::note
242 | Filtering is only available on Android, so you should always check the scanned NFC tag contents.
243 | 
244 | The mime type is case sensitive and must be provided with lower case letters.
245 | :::
246 | 
247 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
248 | 
249 | <TabItem label="JavaScript">
250 | 
251 | ```javascript
252 | import { scan, TechKind } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-nfc';
253 | 
254 | const techLists = [
255 |   // capture anything using NfcF
256 |   [TechKind.NfcF],
257 |   // capture all MIFARE Classics with NDEF payloads
258 |   [TechKind.NfcA, TechKind.MifareClassic, TechKind.Ndef],
259 | ];
260 | 
261 | const tag = await scan({
262 |   type: 'ndef', // or 'tag'
263 |   mimeType: 'text/plain',
264 |   uri: {
265 |     scheme: 'https',
266 |     host: 'my.domain.com',
267 |     pathPrefix: '/app',
268 |   },
269 |   techLists,
270 | });
271 | ```
272 | 
273 | </TabItem>
274 | 
275 | <TabItem label="Rust">
276 | 
277 | ```rust
278 | tauri::Builder::default()
279 |   .setup(|app| {
280 |     #[cfg(mobile)]
281 |     {
282 |       use tauri_plugin_nfc::NfcExt;
283 | 
284 |       app.handle().plugin(tauri_plugin_nfc::init());
285 | 
286 |       let tag = app
287 |         .nfc()
288 |         .scan(tauri_plugin_nfc::ScanRequest {
289 |             kind: tauri_plugin_nfc::ScanKind::Ndef {
290 |                 mime_type: Some("text/plain".to_string()),
291 |                 uri: Some(tauri_plugin_nfc::UriFilter {
292 |                   scheme: Some("https".to_string()),
293 |                   host: Some("my.domain.com".to_string()),
294 |                   path_prefix: Some("/app".to_string()),
295 |                 }),
296 |                 tech_list: Some(vec![
297 |                   vec![tauri_plugin_nfc::TechKind::Ndef],
298 |                 ]),
299 |             },
300 |         })?
301 |         .tag;
302 |     }
303 |     Ok(())
304 |   })
305 | ```
306 | 
307 | </TabItem>
308 | 
309 | </Tabs>
310 | 
311 | ### Writing to NFC tags
312 | 
313 | The `write` API can be used to write a payload to a NFC tag.
314 | If there's no scanned tag with `keepSessionAlive: true`, the application will first scan an NFC tag.
315 | 
316 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
317 | 
318 | <TabItem label="JavaScript">
319 | 
320 | ```javascript
321 | import { write, textRecord, uriRecord } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-nfc';
322 | 
323 | const payload = [uriRecord('https://tauri.app'), textRecord('some payload')];
324 | 
325 | const options = {
326 |   // the kind is only required if you do not have a scanned tag session alive
327 |   // its format is the same as the argument provided to scan()
328 |   kind: {
329 |     type: 'ndef',
330 |   },
331 |   // configure the messages displayed in the "Scan NFC" dialog on iOS
332 |   message: 'Scan a NFC tag',
333 |   successfulReadMessage: 'NFC tag successfully scanned',
334 |   successMessage: 'NFC tag successfully written',
335 | };
336 | 
337 | await write(payload, options);
338 | ```
339 | 
340 | </TabItem>
341 | 
342 | <TabItem label="Rust">
343 | :::caution
344 | The Rust API currently only provides a low level interface for writing NFC payloads.
345 | 
346 | The API will be enhanced soon.
347 | :::
348 | 
349 | ```rust
350 | tauri::Builder::default()
351 |   .setup(|app| {
352 |     #[cfg(mobile)]
353 |     {
354 |       use tauri_plugin_nfc::NfcExt;
355 | 
356 |       app.handle().plugin(tauri_plugin_nfc::init());
357 | 
358 |       app
359 |         .nfc()
360 |         .write(vec![
361 |           tauri_plugin_nfc::NfcRecord {
362 |             format: tauri_plugin_nfc::NFCTypeNameFormat::NfcWellKnown,
363 |             kind: vec![0x55], // URI record
364 |             id: vec![],
365 |             payload: vec![], // insert payload here
366 |           }
367 |         ])?;
368 |     }
369 |     Ok(())
370 |   })
371 | ```
372 | 
373 | </TabItem>
374 | </Tabs>
375 | 
376 | ## Permissions
377 | 
378 | By default all potentially dangerous plugin commands and scopes are blocked and cannot be accessed. You must modify the permissions in your `capabilities` configuration to enable these.
379 | 
380 | See the [Capabilities Overview](/security/capabilities/) for more information and the [step by step guide](/learn/security/using-plugin-permissions/) to use plugin permissions.
381 | 
382 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" ins={4}
383 | {
384 |   "permissions": [
385 |     ...,
386 |     "nfc:default",
387 |   ]
388 | }
389 | ```
390 | 
