 12 | 
 13 | <PluginLinks plugin={frontmatter.plugin} showJsLinks={false} />
 14 | 
 15 | Ensure that a single instance of your tauri app is running at a time using the Single Instance Plugin.
 16 | 
 17 | ## Supported Platforms
 18 | 
 19 | <Compatibility plugin={frontmatter.plugin} />
 20 | 
 21 | ## Setup
 22 | 
 23 | Install the Single Instance plugin to get started.
 24 | 
 25 | <Tabs>
 26 |   <TabItem label="Automatic">
 27 | 
 28 |     Use your project's package manager to add the dependency:
 29 | 
 30 |     {' '}
 31 | 
 32 |     <CommandTabs
 33 |       npm="npm run tauri add single-instance"
 34 |       yarn="yarn run tauri add single-instance"
 35 |       pnpm="pnpm tauri add single-instance"
 36 |       deno="deno task tauri add single-instance"
 37 |       bun="bun tauri add single-instance"
 38 |       cargo="cargo tauri add single-instance"
 39 |     />
 40 | 
 41 |   </TabItem>
 42 |     <TabItem label="Manual">
 43 |       <Steps>
 44 | 
 45 |         1. Run the following command in the `src-tauri` folder to add the plugin to the project's dependencies in `Cargo.toml`:
 46 | 
 47 |             ```sh frame=none
 48 |             cargo add tauri-plugin-single-instance --target 'cfg(any(target_os = "macos", windows, target_os = "linux"))'
 49 |             ```
 50 | 
 51 |         2.  Modify `lib.rs` to initialize the plugin:
 52 | 
 53 |             ```rust title="lib.rs" ins={5-6}
 54 |             #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
 55 |             pub fn run() {
 56 |                 tauri::Builder::default()
 57 |                     .setup(|app| {
 58 |                         #[cfg(desktop)]
 59 |                         app.handle().plugin(tauri_plugin_single_instance::init(|app, args, cwd| {}));
 60 |                         Ok(())
 61 |                     })
 62 |                     .run(tauri::generate_context!())
 63 |                     .expect("error while running tauri application");
 64 |             }
 65 |             ```
 66 | 
 67 |       </Steps>
 68 |     </TabItem>
 69 | 
 70 | </Tabs>
 71 | 
 72 | ## Usage
 73 | 
 74 | The plugin is already installed and initialized, and it should be functioning correctly right away. Nevertheless, we can also enhance its functionality with the `init()` method.
 75 | 
 76 | The plugin `init()` method takes a closure that is invoked when a new app instance was started, but closed by the plugin.
 77 | The closure has three arguments:
 78 | 
 79 |   <Steps>
 80 | 
 81 | 1. **`app`:** The [AppHandle](https://docs.rs/tauri/2.0.0/tauri/struct.AppHandle.html) of the application.
 82 | 2. **`args`:** The list of arguments, that was passed by the user to initiate this new instance.
 83 | 3. **`cwd`:** The Current Working Directory denotes the directory from which the new application instance was launched.
 84 | 
 85 |   </Steps>
 86 | 
 87 | So, the closure should look like below
 88 | 
 89 | ```rust
 90 | .plugin(tauri_plugin_single_instance::init(|app, args, cwd| {
 91 |   // Write your code here...
 92 | }))
 93 | ```
 94 | 
 95 | ### Focusing on New Instance
 96 | 
 97 | By default, when you initiate a new instance while the application is already running, no action is taken. To focus the window of the running instance when user tries to open a new instance, alter the callback closure as follows:
 98 | 
 99 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs" {1} {5-12}
100 | use tauri::{AppHandle, Manager};
101 | 
102 | pub fn run() {
