201 | ## Migrations
202 | 
203 | This plugin supports database migrations, allowing you to manage database schema evolution over time.
204 | 
205 | ### Defining Migrations
206 | 
207 | Migrations are defined in Rust using the [`Migration`](https://docs.rs/tauri-plugin-sql/latest/tauri_plugin_sql/struct.Migration.html) struct. Each migration should include a unique version number, a description, the SQL to be executed, and the type of migration (Up or Down).
208 | 
209 | Example of a migration:
210 | 
211 | ```rust
212 | use tauri_plugin_sql::{Migration, MigrationKind};
213 | 
214 | let migration = Migration {
215 |     version: 1,
216 |     description: "create_initial_tables",
217 |     sql: "CREATE TABLE users (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT);",
218 |     kind: MigrationKind::Up,
219 | };
220 | ````
221 | 
222 | ### Adding Migrations to the Plugin Builder
223 | 
224 | Migrations are registered with the [`Builder`](https://docs.rs/tauri-plugin-sql/latest/tauri_plugin_sql/struct.Builder.html) struct provided by the plugin. Use the `add_migrations` method to add your migrations to the plugin for a specific database connection.
225 | 
226 | Example of adding migrations:
227 | 
228 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/main.rs" {1} {6-11} {17}
229 | use tauri_plugin_sql::{Builder, Migration, MigrationKind};
230 | 
231 | fn main() {
232 |     let migrations = vec![
233 |         // Define your migrations here
234 |         Migration {
235 |             version: 1,
236 |             description: "create_initial_tables",
237 |             sql: "CREATE TABLE users (id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY, name TEXT);",
238 |             kind: MigrationKind::Up,
239 |         }
240 |     ];
241 | 
242 |     tauri::Builder::default()
243 |         .plugin(
244 |             tauri_plugin_sql::Builder::default()
245 |                 .add_migrations("sqlite:mydatabase.db", migrations)
246 |                 .build(),
247 |         )
248 |         ...
249 | }
250 | ```
251 | 
252 | ### Applying Migrations
253 | 
254 | To apply the migrations when the plugin is initialized, add the connection string to the `tauri.conf.json` file:
255 | 
256 | ```json title="src-tauri/tauri.conf.json" {3-5}
257 | {
258 |   "plugins": {
259 |     "sql": {
260 |       "preload": ["sqlite:mydatabase.db"]
261 |     }
262 |   }
263 | }
264 | ```
265 | 
266 | Alternatively, the client side `load()` also runs the migrations for a given connection string:
267 | 
268 | ```ts
269 | import Database from '@tauri-apps/plugin-sql';
270 | const db = await Database.load('sqlite:mydatabase.db');
271 | ```
272 | 
273 | Ensure that the migrations are defined in the correct order and are safe to run multiple times.
274 | 
275 | ### Migration Management
276 | 
277 | - **Version Control**: Each migration must have a unique version number. This is crucial for ensuring the migrations are applied in the correct order.
278 | - **Idempotency**: Write migrations in a way that they can be safely re-run without causing errors or unintended consequences.
279 | - **Testing**: Thoroughly test migrations to ensure they work as expected and do not compromise the integrity of your database.
280 | 
281 | ## Permissions
282 | 
283 | By default all potentially dangerous plugin commands and scopes are blocked and cannot be accessed. You must modify the permissions in your `capabilities` configuration to enable these.
284 | 
285 | See the [Capabilities Overview](/security/capabilities/) for more information and the [step by step guide](/learn/security/using-plugin-permissions/) to use plugin permissions.
286 | 
287 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" ins={4-5}
288 | {
289 |   "permissions": [
290 |     ...,
291 |     "sql:default",
292 |     "sql:allow-execute",
293 |   ]
294 | }
295 | ```
296 | 
