 81 | ## Signing updates
 82 | 
 83 | Tauri's updater needs a signature to verify that the update is from a trusted source. This cannot be disabled.
 84 | 
 85 | To sign your updates you need two keys:
 86 | 
 87 | 1. The public key, which will be set in the `tauri.conf.json` to validate the artifacts before the installation. This public key can be uploaded and shared safely as long as your private key is secure.
 88 | 2. The private key, which is used to sign your installer files. You should NEVER share this key with anyone. Also, if you lose this key you will NOT be able to publish new updates to the users that have the app already installed. It is important to store this key in a safe place!
 89 | 
 90 | To generate the keys the Tauri CLI provides the `signer generate` command. You can run this to create the keys in the home folder:
 91 | 
 92 | <Tabs>
 93 |   <CommandTabs
 94 |     npm="npm run tauri signer generate -- -w ~/.tauri/myapp.key"
 95 |     yarn="yarn tauri signer generate -w ~/.tauri/myapp.key"
 96 |     pnpm="pnpm tauri signer generate -w ~/.tauri/myapp.key"
 97 |     deno="deno task tauri signer generate -w ~/.tauri/myapp.key"
 98 |     bun="bunx tauri signer generate -w ~/.tauri/myapp.key"
 99 |     cargo="cargo tauri signer generate -w ~/.tauri/myapp.key"
100 |   />
101 | </Tabs>
102 | 
103 | ### Building
104 | 
105 | While building your update artifacts, you need to have the private key you generated above in your environment variables. `.env` files do _not_ work!
106 | 
107 | <Tabs>
108 |   <TabItem label="Mac/Linux">
109 |   ```sh frame=none
110 |   export TAURI_SIGNING_PRIVATE_KEY="Path or content of your private key"
111 |   # optionally also add a password
112 |   export TAURI_SIGNING_PRIVATE_KEY_PASSWORD=""
113 |   ```
114 |   </TabItem>
115 |   <TabItem label="Windows">
116 |   Run this in `PowerShell`:
117 |   ```ps frame=none
118 |   $env:TAURI_SIGNING_PRIVATE_KEY="Path or content of your private key"
119 |   <# optionally also add a password #>
120 |   $env:TAURI_SIGNING_PRIVATE_KEY_PASSWORD=""
121 |   ```
122 |   </TabItem>
123 | </Tabs>
124 | 
125 | After that, you can run Tauri build as usual and Tauri will generate the update bundles and their signatures.
126 | The generated files depend on the [`createUpdaterArtifacts`] configuration value configured below.
127 | 
128 | <Tabs>
129 |   <TabItem label="v2">
130 | 
131 | ```json
132 | {
133 |   "bundle": {
134 |     "createUpdaterArtifacts": true
135 |   }
136 | }
137 | ```
138 | 
139 | On Linux, Tauri will create the normal AppImage inside the `target/release/bundle/appimage/` folder:
140 | 
141 | - `myapp.AppImage` - The standard app bundle. It will be re-used by the updater.
142 | - `myapp.AppImage.sig` - The signature of the updater bundle.
143 | 
144 | On macOS, Tauri will create a .tar.gz archive from the application bundle inside the target/release/bundle/macos/ folder:
145 | 
146 | - `myapp.app` - The standard app bundle.
147 | - `myapp.app.tar.gz` - The updater bundle.
148 | - `myapp.app.tar.gz.sig` - The signature of the update bundle.
149 | 
150 | On Windows, Tauri will create the normal MSI and NSIS installers inside the target/release/bundle/msi/ and target/release/bundle/nsis folders:
151 | 
152 | - `myapp-setup.exe` - The standard app bundle. It will be re-used by the updater.
153 | - `myapp-setup.exe.sig` - The signature of the update bundle.
154 | - `myapp.msi` - The standard app bundle. It will be re-used by the updater.
155 | - `myapp.msi.sig` - The signature of the update bundle.
156 | 
157 | {''}
158 | 
159 | </TabItem>
160 | <TabItem label="v1 compatible">
161 | 
162 | ```json
163 | {
164 |   "bundle": {
165 |     "createUpdaterArtifacts": "v1Compatible"
166 |   }
167 | }
168 | ```
169 | 
