196 | ## Tauri Configuration
197 | 
198 | Set up the `tauri.conf.json` in this format for the updater to start working.
199 | 
200 | | Keys                                 | Description                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    |
201 | | ------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
202 | | `createUpdaterArtifacts`             | Setting this to `true` tells Tauri's app bundler to create updater artifacts. If you're migrating your app from an older Tauri version, set it to `"v1Compatible"` instead. **This setting will be removed in v3** so make sure to change it to `true` once all your users are migrated to v2. |
203 | | `pubkey`                             | This has to be the public key generated from the Tauri CLI in the step above. It **cannot** be a file path!                                                                                                                                                                                    |
204 | | `endpoints`                          | This must be an array of endpoint URLs as strings. TLS is enforced in production mode. Tauri will only continue to the next url if a non-2XX status code is returned!                                                                                                                          |
205 | | `dangerousInsecureTransportProtocol` | Setting this to `true` allows the updater to accept non-HTTPS endpoints. Use this configuration with caution!                                                                                                                                                                                  |
206 | 
207 | Each updater URL can contain the following dynamic variables, allowing you to determine server-side if an update is available.
208 | 
209 | - `{{current_version}}`: The version of the app that is requesting the update.
210 | - `{{target}}`: The operating system name (one of `linux`, `windows` or `darwin`).
211 | - `{{arch}}`: The architecture of the machine (one of `x86_64`, `i686`, `aarch64` or `armv7`).
212 | 
213 | ```json title=tauri.conf.json
214 | {
215 |   "bundle": {
216 |     "createUpdaterArtifacts": true
217 |   },
218 |   "plugins": {
219 |     "updater": {
220 |       "pubkey": "CONTENT FROM PUBLICKEY.PEM",
221 |       "endpoints": [
222 |         "https://releases.myapp.com/{{target}}/{{arch}}/{{current_version}}",
223 |         // or a static github json file
224 |         "https://github.com/user/repo/releases/latest/download/latest.json"
225 |       ]
226 |     }
227 |   }
228 | }
229 | ```
230 | 
231 | :::tip
232 | Custom variables are not supported, but you can define a [custom `{{target}}`](#custom-target).
233 | :::
234 | 
235 | ### `installMode` on Windows
236 | 
237 | On Windows there is an additional optional `"installMode"` config to change how the update is installed.
238 | 
239 | ```json title=tauri.conf.json
240 | {
241 |   "plugins": {
242 |     "updater": {
243 |       "windows": {
244 |         "installMode": "passive"
245 |       }
246 |     }
247 |   }
248 | }
249 | ```
250 | 
251 | - `"passive"`: There will be a small window with a progress bar. The update will be installed without requiring any user interaction. Generally recommended and the default mode.
252 | - `"basicUi"`: There will be a basic user interface shown which requires user interaction to finish the installation.
253 | - `"quiet"`: There will be no progress feedback to the user. With this mode the installer cannot request admin privileges by itself so it only works in user-wide installations or when your app itself already runs with admin privileges. Generally not recommended.
254 | 
255 | ## Server Support
256 | 
257 | The updater plugin can be used in two ways. Either with a dynamic update server or a static JSON file (to use on services like S3 or GitHub gists).
258 | 
259 | ### Static JSON File
260 | 
261 | When using static, you just need to return a JSON containing the required information.
262 | 
263 | | Keys        | Description                                                                                                                                                     |
264 | | ----------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
265 | | `version`   | Must be a valid [SemVer](https://semver.org/), with or without a leading `v`, meaning that both `1.0.0` and `v1.0.0` are valid.                                 |
266 | | `notes`     | Notes about the update.                                                                                                                                         |
267 | | `pub_date`  | The date must be formatted according to [RFC 3339](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3339) if present.                                                   |
268 | | `platforms` | Each platform key is in the `OS-ARCH` format, where `OS` is one of `linux`, `darwin` or `windows`, and `ARCH` is one of `x86_64`, `aarch64`, `i686` or `armv7`. |
269 | | `signature` | The content of the generated `.sig` file, which may change with each build. A path or URL does not work!                                                        |
270 | 
271 | :::info
272 | When using [custom targets](#custom-target) the provided target string is matched against the `platforms` key
273 | instead of the default `OS-ARCH` value.
274 | :::
275 | 
276 | The required keys are `"version"`, `"platforms.[target].url"` and `"platforms.[target].signature"`; the others are optional.
277 | 
278 | ```json
279 | {
280 |   "version": "",
281 |   "notes": "",
282 |   "pub_date": "",
283 |   "platforms": {
284 |     "linux-x86_64": {
285 |       "signature": "",
286 |       "url": ""
287 |     },
288 |     "windows-x86_64": {
289 |       "signature": "",
290 |       "url": ""
291 |     },
292 |     "darwin-x86_64": {
293 |       "signature": "",
294 |       "url": ""
295 |     }
296 |   }
297 | }
298 | ```
299 | 
300 | Note that Tauri will validate the whole file before checking the version field, so make sure all existing platform configurations are valid and complete.
301 | 
302 | :::tip
303 | [Tauri Action](https://github.com/tauri-apps/tauri-action) generates a static JSON file for you to use on CDNs such as GitHub Releases.
304 | :::
305 | 
306 | ### Dynamic Update Server
307 | 
308 | When using a dynamic update server, Tauri will follow the server's instructions. To disable the internal version check you can overwrite the [plugin's version comparison](https://docs.rs/tauri-plugin-updater/latest/tauri_plugin_updater/struct.UpdaterBuilder.html#method.version_comparator), this will install the version sent by the server (useful if you need to roll back your app).
309 | 
310 | Your server can use variables defined in the `endpoint` URL above to determine if an update is required. If you need more data, you can include additional [request headers in Rust](https://docs.rs/tauri-plugin-updater/latest/tauri_plugin_updater/struct.UpdaterBuilder.html#method.header) to your liking.
311 | 
312 | Your server should respond with a status code of [`204 No Content`](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc2616#section-10.2.5) if there is no update available.
313 | 
314 | If an update is required, your server should respond with a status code of [`200 OK`](http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2616#section-10.2.1) and a JSON response in this format:
315 | 
316 | | Keys        | Description                                                                                                                          |
317 | | ----------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
318 | | `version`   | This Must be a valid [SemVer](https://semver.org/), with or without a leading `v`, meaning that both `1.0.0` and `v1.0.0` are valid. |
319 | | `notes`     | Notes about the update.                                                                                                              |
320 | | `pub_date`  | The date must be formatted according to [RFC 3339](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc3339) if present.                        |
321 | | `url`       | This Must be a valid URL to the update bundle.                                                                                       |
322 | | `signature` | The content of the generated `.sig` file, which may change with each build. A path or URL does not work!                             |
323 | 
324 | The required keys are `"url"`, `"version"` and `"signature"`; the others are optional.
325 | 
326 | ```json
327 | {
328 |   "version": "",
329 |   "pub_date": "",
330 |   "url": "",
331 |   "signature": "",
332 |   "notes": ""
333 | }
334 | ```
335 | 
336 | :::tip
337 | CrabNebula, an official Tauri partner, offers a dynamic update server. For more information, see the [Distributing with CrabNebula Cloud] documentation.
338 | :::
339 | 
340 | ## Checking for Updates
341 | 
342 | The default API for checking updates and installing them leverages the configured endpoints
343 | and can be accessed by both JavaScript and Rust code.
344 | 
345 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
346 |   <TabItem label="JavaScript">
347 | 
348 | ```js
349 | import { check } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-updater';
350 | import { relaunch } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-process';
351 | 
352 | const update = await check();
353 | if (update) {
354 |   console.log(
355 |     `found update ${update.version} from ${update.date} with notes ${update.body}`
356 |   );
357 |   let downloaded = 0;
358 |   let contentLength = 0;
359 |   // alternatively we could also call update.download() and update.install() separately
360 |   await update.downloadAndInstall((event) => {
361 |     switch (event.event) {
362 |       case 'Started':
363 |         contentLength = event.data.contentLength;
364 |         console.log(`started downloading ${event.data.contentLength} bytes`);
365 |         break;
366 |       case 'Progress':
367 |         downloaded += event.data.chunkLength;
368 |         console.log(`downloaded ${downloaded} from ${contentLength}`);
369 |         break;
370 |       case 'Finished':
371 |         console.log('download finished');
372 |         break;
373 |     }
374 |   });
375 | 
376 |   console.log('update installed');
377 |   await relaunch();
378 | }
379 | ```
380 | 
381 | For more information see the [JavaScript API documentation].
382 | 
383 | </TabItem>
384 | 
385 | <TabItem label="Rust">
386 | 
387 | ```rust title="src-tauri/src/lib.rs"
388 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
389 | 
390 | pub fn run() {
391 |   tauri::Builder::default()
392 |     .setup(|app| {
393 |       let handle = app.handle().clone();
394 |       tauri::async_runtime::spawn(async move {
395 |         update(handle).await.unwrap();
396 |       });
397 |       Ok(())
398 |     })
399 |     .run(tauri::generate_context!())
400 |     .unwrap();
401 | }
402 | 
403 | async fn update(app: tauri::AppHandle) -> tauri_plugin_updater::Result<()> {
404 |   if let Some(update) = app.updater()?.check().await? {
405 |     let mut downloaded = 0;
406 | 
407 |     // alternatively we could also call update.download() and update.install() separately
408 |     update
409 |       .download_and_install(
410 |         |chunk_length, content_length| {
411 |           downloaded += chunk_length;
412 |           println!("downloaded {downloaded} from {content_length:?}");
413 |         },
414 |         || {
415 |           println!("download finished");
416 |         },
417 |       )
418 |       .await?;
419 | 
420 |     println!("update installed");
421 |     app.restart();
422 |   }
423 | 
424 |   Ok(())
425 | }
426 | ```
427 | 
428 | :::tip
429 | To notify the frontend of the download progress consider using a command with a [channel].
430 | 
431 | <details>
432 |   <summary>Updater command</summary>
433 | 
434 | ```rust
435 | #[cfg(desktop)]
436 | mod app_updates {
437 |     use std::sync::Mutex;
438 |     use serde::Serialize;
439 |     use tauri::{ipc::Channel, AppHandle, State};
440 |     use tauri_plugin_updater::{Update, UpdaterExt};
441 | 
442 |     #[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]
443 |     pub enum Error {
444 |         #[error(transparent)]
445 |         Updater(#[from] tauri_plugin_updater::Error),
446 |         #[error("there is no pending update")]
447 |         NoPendingUpdate,
448 |     }
449 | 
450 |     impl Serialize for Error {
451 |         fn serialize<S>(&self, serializer: S) -> std::result::Result<S::Ok, S::Error>
452 |         where
453 |             S: serde::Serializer,
454 |         {
455 |             serializer.serialize_str(self.to_string().as_str())
456 |         }
457 |     }
458 | 
459 |     type Result<T> = std::result::Result<T, Error>;
460 | 
461 |     #[derive(Clone, Serialize)]
462 |     #[serde(tag = "event", content = "data")]
463 |     pub enum DownloadEvent {
464 |         #[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]
465 |         Started {
466 |             content_length: Option<u64>,
467 |         },
468 |         #[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]
469 |         Progress {
470 |             chunk_length: usize,
471 |         },
472 |         Finished,
473 |     }
474 | 
475 |     #[derive(Serialize)]
476 |     #[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")]
477 |     pub struct UpdateMetadata {
478 |         version: String,
479 |         current_version: String,
480 |     }
481 | 
482 |     #[tauri::command]
483 |     pub async fn fetch_update(
484 |         app: AppHandle,
485 |         pending_update: State<'_, PendingUpdate>,
486 |     ) -> Result<Option<UpdateMetadata>> {
487 |         let channel = "stable";
488 |         let url = url::Url::parse(&format!(
489 |             "https://cdn.myupdater.com/{{{{target}}}}-{{{{arch}}}}/{{{{current_version}}}}?channel={channel}",
490 |         )).expect("invalid URL");
491 | 
492 |       let update = app
493 |           .updater_builder()
494 |           .endpoints(vec![url])?
495 |           .build()?
496 |           .check()
497 |           .await?;
498 | 
499 |       let update_metadata = update.as_ref().map(|update| UpdateMetadata {
500 |           version: update.version.clone(),
501 |           current_version: update.current_version.clone(),
502 |       });
503 | 
504 |       *pending_update.0.lock().unwrap() = update;
505 | 
506 |       Ok(update_metadata)
507 |     }
508 | 
509 |     #[tauri::command]
510 |     pub async fn install_update(pending_update: State<'_, PendingUpdate>, on_event: Channel<DownloadEvent>) -> Result<()> {
511 |         let Some(update) = pending_update.0.lock().unwrap().take() else {
512 |             return Err(Error::NoPendingUpdate);
513 |         };
514 | 
515 |         let started = false;
516 | 
517 |         update
518 |             .download_and_install(
519 |                 |chunk_length, content_length| {
520 |                     if !started {
521 |                         let _ = on_event.send(DownloadEvent::Started { content_length });
522 |                         started = true;
523 |                     }
524 | 
525 |                     let _ = on_event.send(DownloadEvent::Progress { chunk_length });
526 |                 },
527 |                 || {
528 |                     let _ = on_event.send(DownloadEvent::Finished);
529 |                 },
530 |             )
531 |             .await?;
532 | 
533 |         Ok(())
534 |     }
535 | 
536 |     struct PendingUpdate(Mutex<Option<Update>>);
537 | }
538 | 
539 | #[cfg_attr(mobile, tauri::mobile_entry_point)]
540 | pub fn run() {
541 |     tauri::Builder::default()
542 |         .plugin(tauri_plugin_process::init())
543 |         .setup(|app| {
544 |             #[cfg(desktop)]
545 |             {
546 |                 app.handle().plugin(tauri_plugin_updater::Builder::new().build());
547 |                 app.manage(app_updates::PendingUpdate(Mutex::new(None)));
548 |             }
549 |             Ok(())
550 |         })
551 |         .invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![
552 |             #[cfg(desktop)]
553 |             app_updates::fetch_update,
554 |             #[cfg(desktop)]
555 |             app_updates::install_update
556 |         ])
557 | }
558 | ```
559 | 
560 | </details>
561 | :::
562 | 
563 | For more information see the [Rust API documentation].
564 | 
565 | </TabItem>
566 | </Tabs>
567 | 
568 | Note that restarting your app immediately after installing an update is not required and you can choose
569 | how to handle the update by either waiting until the user manually restarts the app, or prompting him to select when to do so.
570 | 
571 | :::note
572 | On Windows the application is automatically exited when the install step is executed due to a limitation of Windows installers.
573 | :::
574 | 
575 | When checking and downloading updates it is possible to define a custom request timeout, a proxy and request headers.
576 | 
577 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
578 | <TabItem label="JavaScript">
579 | 
580 | ```js
581 | import { check } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-updater';
582 | 
583 | const update = await check({
584 |   proxy: '<proxy url>',
585 |   timeout: 30000 /* milliseconds */,
586 |   headers: {
587 |     Authorization: 'Bearer <token>',
588 |   },
589 | });
590 | ```
591 | 
592 |   </TabItem>
593 | 
594 |   <TabItem label="Rust">
595 | 
596 | ```rust
597 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
598 | let update = app
599 |   .updater_builder()
600 |   .timeout(std::time::Duration::from_secs(30))
601 |   .proxy("<proxy-url>".parse().expect("invalid URL"))
602 |   .header("Authorization", "Bearer <token>")
603 |   .build()?
604 |   .check()
605 |   .await?;
606 | ```
607 | 
608 |   </TabItem>
609 | </Tabs>
610 | 
611 | ### Runtime Configuration
612 | 
613 | The updater APIs also allows the updater to be configured at runtime for more flexibility.
614 | For security reasons some APIs are only available for Rust.
615 | 
616 | #### Endpoints
617 | 
618 | Setting the URLs that should be requested to check updates at runtime allows
619 | more dynamic updates such as separate release channels:
620 | 
621 | ```rust
622 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
623 | let channel = if beta { "beta" } else { "stable" };
624 | let update_url = format!("https://{channel}.myserver.com/{{{{target}}}}-{{{{arch}}}}/{{{{current_version}}}}");
625 | 
626 | let update = app
627 |   .updater_builder()
628 |   .endpoints(vec![update_url])?
629 |   .build()?
630 |   .check()
631 |   .await?;
632 | ```
633 | 
634 | :::tip
635 | Note that when using format!() to interpolate the update URL you need double escapes for the variables
636 | e.g. `{{{{target}}}}`.
637 | :::
638 | 
639 | #### Public key
640 | 
641 | Setting the public key at runtime can be useful to implement a key rotation logic.
642 | It can be set by either the plugin builder or updater builder:
643 | 
644 | ```rust
645 | tauri_plugin_updater::Builder::new().pubkey("<your public key>").build()
646 | ```
647 | 
648 | ```rust
649 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
650 | 
651 | let update = app
652 |   .updater_builder()
653 |   .pubkey("<your public key>")
654 |   .build()?
655 |   .check()
656 |   .await?;
657 | ```
658 | 
659 | #### Custom target
660 | 
661 | By default the updater lets you use the `{{target}}` and `{{arch}}` variables to determine which update asset must be delivered.
662 | If you need more information on your updates (e.g. when distributing a Universal macOS binary option or having more build flavors)
663 | you can set a custom target.
664 | 
665 | <Tabs syncKey="lang">
666 | <TabItem label="JavaScript">
667 | 
668 | ```js
669 | import { check } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-updater';
670 | 
671 | const update = await check({
672 |   target: 'macos-universal',
673 | });
674 | ```
675 | 
676 |   </TabItem>
677 | 
678 |   <TabItem label="Rust">
679 | 
680 | Custom targets can be set by either the plugin builder or updater builder:
681 | 
682 | ```rust
683 | tauri_plugin_updater::Builder::new().target("macos-universal").build()
684 | ```
685 | 
686 | ```rust
687 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
688 | let update = app
689 |   .updater_builder()
690 |   .target("macos-universal")
691 |   .build()?
692 |   .check()
693 |   .await?;
694 | ```
695 | 
696 | :::tip
697 | The default `$target-$arch` key can be retrieved using `tauri_plugin_updater::target()`
698 | which returns an `Option<String>` that is `None` when the updater is not supported on the current platform.
699 | :::
700 | 
701 |   </TabItem>
702 | </Tabs>
703 | 
704 | :::note
705 | 
706 | - When using a custom target it might be easier to use it exclusively to determine the update platform,
707 |   so you could remove the `{{arch}}` variable.
708 | - The value provided as target is the key that is matched against the platform key when using a [Static JSON file](#static-json-file).
709 | 
710 | :::
711 | 
712 | #### Allowing downgrades
713 | 
714 | By default Tauri checks if the update version is greater than the current app version to verify if it should update or not.
715 | To allow downgrades, you must use the updater builder's `version_comparator` API:
716 | 
717 | ```rust
718 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
719 | 
720 | let update = app
721 |   .updater_builder()
722 |   .version_comparator(|current, update| {
723 |     // default comparison: `update.version > current`
724 |     update.version != current
725 |   })
726 |   .build()?
727 |   .check()
728 |   .await?;
729 | ```
730 | 
731 | #### Windows before exit hook
732 | 
733 | Due to a limitation of Windows installers, Tauri will automatically quit your application before installing updates on Windows.
734 | To perform an action before that happens, use the `on_before_exit` function:
735 | 
736 | ```rust
737 | use tauri_plugin_updater::UpdaterExt;
738 | 
739 | let update = app
740 |   .updater_builder()
741 |   .on_before_exit(|| {
742 |     println!("app is about to exit on Windows!");
743 |   })
744 |   .build()?
745 |   .check()
746 |   .await?;
747 | ```
748 | 
749 | :::note
750 | The values from the [configuration](#tauri-configuration) are used as fallback if any of the builder values are not set.
751 | :::
752 | 
753 | [`createUpdaterArtifacts`]: /reference/config/#createupdaterartifacts
754 | [Distributing with CrabNebula Cloud]: /distribute/crabnebula-cloud/
755 | [channel]: /develop/calling-frontend/#channels
756 | [JavaScript API Documentation]: /reference/javascript/updater/
757 | [Rust API Documentation]: https://docs.rs/tauri-plugin-updater
758 | 
759 | ## Permissions
760 | 
761 | By default all potentially dangerous plugin commands and scopes are blocked and cannot be accessed. You must modify the permissions in your `capabilities` configuration to enable these.
762 | 
763 | See the [Capabilities Overview](/security/capabilities/) for more information and the [step by step guide](/learn/security/using-plugin-permissions/) to use plugin permissions.
764 | 
765 | ```json title="src-tauri/capabilities/default.json" ins={4}
766 | {
767 |   "permissions": [
768 |     ...,
769 |     "updater:default",
770 |   ]
771 | }
772 | ```
