 83 | ## Usage
 84 | 
 85 | After adding the window-state plugin, all windows will remember their state when the app is being closed and will restore to their previous state on the next launch.
 86 | 
 87 | You can also access the window-state plugin in both JavaScript and Rust.
 88 | 
 89 | ### JavaScript
 90 | 
 91 | You can use `saveWindowState` to manually save the window state:
 92 | 
 93 | ```javascript
 94 | import { saveWindowState, StateFlags } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-window-state';
 95 | // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
 96 | // const { saveWindowState, StateFlags } = window.__TAURI__.windowState;
 97 | 
 98 | saveWindowState(StateFlags.ALL);
 99 | ```
100 | 
101 | Similarly you can manually restore a window's state from disk:
102 | 
103 | ```javascript
104 | import {
105 |   restoreStateCurrent,
106 |   StateFlags,
107 | } from '@tauri-apps/plugin-window-state';
108 | // when using `"withGlobalTauri": true`, you may use
109 | // const { restoreStateCurrent, StateFlags } = window.__TAURI__.windowState;
110 | 
111 | restoreStateCurrent(StateFlags.ALL);
112 | ```
113 | 
114 | ### Rust
115 | 
116 | You can use the `save_window_state()` method exposed by the `AppHandleExt` trait:
117 | 
118 | ```rust
119 | use tauri_plugin_window_state::{AppHandleExt, StateFlags};
120 | 
121 | // `tauri::AppHandle` now has the following additional method
122 | app.save_window_state(StateFlags::all()); // will save the state of all open windows to disk
123 | ```
124 | 
125 | Similarly you can manually restore a window's state from disk using the `restore_state()` method exposed by the `WindowExt` trait:
126 | 
127 | ```rust
128 | use tauri_plugin_window_state::{WindowExt, StateFlags};
129 | 
130 | // all `Window` types now have the following additional method
131 | window.restore_state(StateFlags::all()); // will restore the window's state from disk
132 | ```
